exhausting and exhilarating. It is one of the  

298
00:27:17,440 --> 00:27:22,840
most ridiculous luxuries of product development, 
is working on a product that many people use and  

299
00:27:22,840 --> 00:27:27,920
therefore you get that much feedback around.
And it was a very common thing for us to hear  

300
00:27:27,920 --> 00:27:32,200
people say, "What are you all doing over 
there? The product hasn't changed in eight  

301
00:27:32,200 --> 00:27:38,880
years." And that was horrible to hear, and 
I felt it too, as a critic on the sidelines,  

302
00:27:38,880 --> 00:27:43,160
as a user who wasn't an employee who eventually 
became an employee, I had the same feedback. And  

303
00:27:43,160 --> 00:27:50,840
so that was my mission. I was like, I am somehow 
ridiculously in this fortunate position that I've  

304
00:27:50,840 --> 00:27:58,200
been entrusted some responsibility here. I might 
flame out completely, but hell if I don't try. And  

305
00:27:58,200 --> 00:28:06,000
so that was both fun and exhausting, like I said.
But it was as simple as starting with we are  

306
00:28:06,000 --> 00:28:11,040
voracious users of the product ourselves, and if 
we aren't, by the way, that's its own problem. I  

307
00:28:11,040 --> 00:28:17,360
think that in order to build something wonderful, 
you have to be a customer of the product. And  

308
00:28:17,360 --> 00:28:20,680
sure, I'm sure you could point to businesses and 
products where that's not the case, and I'm sure  

309
00:28:20,680 --> 00:28:26,160
there's a flaw in that philosophy somewhere, but 
I've always believed that one of the best ways  

310
00:28:26,160 --> 00:28:31,640
to build products is to be a customer yourself 
and to find your own pain points and to build  

311
00:28:31,640 --> 00:28:36,880
