344
00:31:36,560 --> 00:31:41,400
"Don't work on this. It's bad for your career." 
As a microcosm for some of the cultural challenge  

345
00:31:41,400 --> 00:31:46,200
we had around trying big, bold bets, which by 
the way, this wasn't even a big, bold bet. It  

346
00:31:46,200 --> 00:31:51,240
was such an innocuous thing to try. But there 
was a lot of that and it made it very difficult  

347
00:31:51,240 --> 00:32:01,400
without some sheer force of will and also just 
a lot of effort. So there was a lot of that.

348
00:32:01,400 --> 00:32:06,320
Kayvon, there's fractals of stories that I could 
infinitely follow. There's so much interesting  

349
00:32:06,320 --> 00:32:12,040
stuff here. One that just stands out is this 
idea of the sacred cows become your future  

350
00:32:12,040 --> 00:32:15,840
roadmap. It's like flipping it from here's the 
thing that we're all afraid of. No, this is not  

351
00:32:15,840 --> 00:32:20,280
what we should be doing. I think that's really 
interesting and could be a lesson to people. 

352
00:32:20,280 --> 00:32:25,520
The other is just, I love this point you made 
about the growth was most accelerant when you're  

353
00:32:25,520 --> 00:32:30,120
just focusing on the core, that's what actually 
... Like optimize, people bash on optimizing the  

354
00:32:30,120 --> 00:32:34,560
existing experience and just micro-optimizing, 
improving, versus trying to take all these big,  

355
00:32:34,560 --> 00:32:37,880
bold bets and experiments. Obviously, that's 
also valuable. But I think it's really  

356
00:32:37,880 --> 00:32:44,520
interesting that that's what reignited growth 
and was responsible for growth for a while.

357
00:32:44,520 --> 00:32:53,320
And continue to be, by the way. One of the 
lines that we had to maneuver was creating  

358
00:32:53,320 --> 00:32:59,800
a portfolio of bets where some of them were 
not speculative at all. We knew that if we  

359
00:32:59,800 --> 00:33:06,720
continue to invest in ML and getting better 
with recommendations in the main feed and  

360
00:33:06,720 --> 00:33:12,400
through notifications and things like improving 
the onboarding flow, it was rife with opportunity. 

361
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:18,600
You'd have really dumb things happen. We 
would learn. There was one just bizarre  

362
00:33:18,600 --> 00:33:23,680
and incredible meeting we had where we finally 
had got more rigorous around instrumenting our  

363
00:33:23,680 --> 00:33:29,760
onboarding flow. And we found that in a 
couple countries, like we had a bug with  

364
00:33:29,760 --> 00:33:36,480
our SMS verification flow where we wanted to 
verify users who were signing up with a phone  

365
00:33:36,480 --> 00:33:41,000
number and our telco integration to send SMS 
verification cards just wasn't working. And  

366
00:33:41,000 --> 00:33:46,720
so a huge percentage of people signing up in the 
UAE and other countries just couldn't use Twitter. 

367
00:33:46,720 --> 00:33:50,760
And so of course at the scale that we were 
operating in with hundreds of millions of users,  

368
00:33:50,760 --> 00:33:55,840
you need to be able to refine the basic building 
blocks of the product, and that's going to lead  

369
00:33:55,840 --> 00:34:03,160
to reliable growth. But we wanted to balance 
that with a portfolio of other bets and product  

370
00:34:03,160 --> 00:34:08,440
improvements that would materially add new 
capabilities. And that was a balance that I  

371
00:34:08,440 --> 00:34:14,640
don't think existed. And by the way, I don't 
think we nailed it either under my tenure,  

372
00:34:14,640 --> 00:34:20,520
but it was the driving force of what I wanted to 
achieve, was to create a better balance that would  

373
00:34:20,520 --> 00:34:28,000
result in evolving the product and introducing new 
capabilities. And so that's what we tried to do.

374
00:34:28,000 --> 00:34:32,120
In terms of what actually helped turn things 
around, things that I kind of gathered from  

375
00:34:32,120 --> 00:34:35,320
what you shared so far, one is just building 
a little momentum, having some quick wins of  

376
00:34:35,320 --> 00:34:39,560
new products that people start to get excited 
about. So creating more excitement down the,  

377
00:34:39,560 --> 00:34:43,800
oh wow, we can actually try new things. There's 
also, it felt like there's a sense of trust  

378
00:34:43,800 --> 00:34:47,920
that you built with Jack and execs of just 
like, okay, we can actually trust this team. 

379
00:34:47,920 --> 00:34:51,760
Also, it feels like because growth started 
up, there's probably a sense of like, okay,  

380
00:34:51,760 --> 00:34:56,640
we can try some new crazy ideas. It feels 
like another part of your strategy was  

381
00:34:56,640 --> 00:35:00,160
[inaudible 00:34:56] hires and bringing 
in these entrepreneurial folks to take  

382
00:35:00,160 --> 00:35:03,360
the lead on some of these big ideas. Can 
you talk about that? Was that something  

383
00:35:03,360 --> 00:35:07,320
you actively thought about and was 
that a big part of the impact there?

384
00:35:07,320 --> 00:35:12,640
Totally. Yeah. So I think a couple things. One, 
the only thing I'd add to what you said in terms  

385
00:35:12,640 --> 00:35:18,920
of the ingredients, it was also just storytelling 
and just repetitive storytelling around this is  

386
00:35:18,920 --> 00:35:22,680
the vision, these are the bets we're making. 
Here's why. And you can't just tell that  

387
00:35:22,680 --> 00:35:26,440
story once. I'm talking internally, by the way. 
There's a whole other component of this, which  

388
00:35:26,440 --> 00:35:32,200
is externally how do you tell, especially for a 
product like Twitter where it's a consumer product  

389
00:35:32,200 --> 00:35:35,480
that hundreds of millions of people are using, 
and you have many constituents, you have users,  

390
00:35:35,480 --> 00:35:40,400
you have advertisers. And so it was very important 
for us to tell the story of here's what we're  

391
00:35:40,400 --> 00:35:44,800
doing and why. Here's why you should believe in 
us. And by the way, give us all your constructive  

392
00:35:44,800 --> 00:35:49,240
criticism too, because we're listening and 
we're going to build that into ... So that  

393
00:35:49,240 --> 00:35:53,960
storytelling was really, really important.
And this is oversimplifying the world,  

394
00:35:53,960 --> 00:35:58,680
but there's two types of internal team members. 
There are people who hear that story, who have  

395
00:35:58,680 --> 00:36:02,320
been a part of the organization who's been slow, 
or maybe they've been outside the company as a  

396
00:36:02,320 --> 00:36:05,160
user of Twitter, and they're like, I'd never 
really want to work there because it doesn't  

397
00:36:05,160 --> 00:36:09,440
seem like a particularly ambitious product 
company. And one of two things happens when  

398
00:36:09,440 --> 00:36:15,120
you hear that story. Either you're inspired and 
you're like, yeah, we can finally take a swing at  

399
00:36:15,120 --> 00:36:18,080
making this product better. And maybe I wasn't 
interested in working in this company before,  

400
00:36:18,080 --> 00:36:22,520
but I mean, this is an iconic product, and to 
have an opportunity to reshape it is really  

401
00:36:22,520 --> 00:36:29,280
exciting. Or again, oversimplified world, but 
there are people who are very pessimistic and  

402
00:36:29,280 --> 00:36:33,680
maybe aren't excited by that vision. Let's just 
stick to what we know works. We're not going to  

403
00:36:33,680 --> 00:36:37,800
take any big swings. That's a waste of time.
I think one of the really important things  

404
00:36:37,800 --> 00:36:44,800
about driving cultural change at the leadership 
level is you've got to identify whether someone's  

405
00:36:44,800 --> 00:36:50,560
on the wagon or off the wagon and either quickly 
convince them to get on the wagon or if they're  

406
00:36:50,560 --> 00:36:54,960
not on the wagon, they shouldn't be there. 
And that's something that we were terrible at,  

407
00:36:54,960 --> 00:36:59,040
and we didn't have the organizational 
structure to be able to enact that.

408
00:36:59,040 --> 00:37:03,280
The wagon is they're excited and bought 
into this vision and want this to happen?

409
00:37:03,280 --> 00:37:07,320
Correct, and contribute towards it. And off the 
wagon is like you're not at the company. And we  

410
00:37:07,320 --> 00:37:10,600
didn't have an organizational structure 
that could allow for that, nor frankly,  

411
00:37:10,600 --> 00:37:15,000
the fortitude. I include myself in this. I 
feel like I've learned a lot about how to  

412
00:37:15,000 --> 00:37:21,080
make that determination. So I think we were 
terrible at that. And Elon is the whatever,  

413
00:37:21,080 --> 00:37:23,600
if that's a spectrum, Elon is the 
opposite spectrum of that. His  

414
00:37:23,600 --> 00:37:27,880
tolerance for people who are not aligned and 
his tolerance for low performance is famously  

415
00:37:27,880 --> 00:37:34,960
extremely low. And I think it's one of the things 
that when I say A/B test, it's very interesting to  

416
00:37:34,960 --> 00:37:40,560
see the extreme to which he has operated.
And I think I've learned a ton around,  

417
00:37:41,840 --> 00:37:46,200
we didn't have the organizational structure 
nor the fortitude to be swifter, and that made  

418
00:37:46,200 --> 00:37:52,280
cultural change way slower. We still were able to 
change the culture, not as much as we should have,  

419
00:37:52,280 --> 00:37:56,960
and certainly not as quickly as we should have or 
efficiently as we should have. Because by the way,  

420
00:37:56,960 --> 00:38:04,160
a lot of high performers who are aligned with that 
desire to change and build, they don't have the,  

421
00:38:04,160 --> 00:38:08,520
there's not like an equal distribution of 
patients. If you're extremely talented and you're  

422
00:38:08,520 --> 00:38:13,040
dealing with organizational shit, you're going 
to go find someplace else that lets you do your  

423
00:38:13,040 --> 00:38:19,160
craft and have impact. So it's very difficult.
But anyway, going to your question, one of the  

424
00:38:19,160 --> 00:38:27,720
things we found that was a really effective way 
of accelerating cultural change and also helping  

425
00:38:27,720 --> 00:38:35,920
drive some of these product initiatives that were 
particularly speculative was doing small acquires.  

426
00:38:35,920 --> 00:38:42,240
And really the benefit of that was, A, you 
bring in a founder type who is an entrepreneur,  

427
00:38:42,240 --> 00:38:47,400
who drives urgency, who has ambition, who's 
ideally savvy enough to also work in the context  

428
00:38:47,400 --> 00:38:51,440
of a large organization, which sometimes 
is a totally different skillset. I mean,  

429
00:38:51,440 --> 00:38:56,360
it is a totally different skillset. And a 
lot of our most ambitious bets that were  

430
00:38:56,360 --> 00:39:05,000
the riskiest and most misaligned with how the 
product worked or there was no easy staff to  

431
00:39:05,000 --> 00:39:11,440
build on top of, a lot of those bets were driven 
by founders who we basically acquired and said,  

432
00:39:11,440 --> 00:39:15,040
"Here, you are going to run this."
And they believed in it. They were  

433
00:39:15,040 --> 00:39:19,440
able to rally a team around them, and it's all 
the attributes of a startup, but with the canvas  

434
00:39:19,440 --> 00:39:26,920
of a product that hundreds of millions of people 
use and more resources. So Spaces, Communities,  

435
00:39:26,920 --> 00:39:34,000
Community Notes, called Birdwatch back then, 
these were all projects driven by ... Fleets,  

436
00:39:34,000 --> 00:39:41,200
as well. These were all projects that were run by 
small teams led by entrepreneurs who we acquired,  

437
00:39:41,200 --> 00:39:48,200
like Keith Coleman runs Community Notes, last 
Birdwatch. He actually was my predecessor. We  

438
00:39:48,200 --> 00:39:51,720
acquired his company so that he could be the 
head of product. And then when he moved on  

439
00:39:51,720 --> 00:39:57,400
from that role, he was extremely passionate 
about this idea of crowdsource moderation and  

440
00:39:57,400 --> 00:40:03,520
letting people annotate misleading content on the 
platform without Twitter acting as a policeman. 

441
00:40:03,520 --> 00:40:07,920
And that was a very speculative bet that by 
the way, a lot of people thought, most people  

442
00:40:07,920 --> 00:40:16,520
thought was a terrible idea. We gave Keith a 
little silo to go build this vision, and then  

443
00:40:17,200 --> 00:40:22,760
it was our job to make sure that bet didn't get 
suffocated in the context of a big organization  

444
00:40:22,760 --> 00:40:29,120
that would otherwise have not had patience for it.
All of the community effort or the creator efforts  

445
00:40:29,120 --> 00:40:33,680
started with Super Follows and tipping, and all 
these things were led by Esther Crawford, whose  

446
00:40:33,680 --> 00:40:39,920
company we acquired and who had her own couple 
of viral moments with the Elon acquisition. But  

447
00:40:39,920 --> 00:40:45,520
she's a phenomenal leader who, again, is a perfect 
example of balancing that entrepreneurial startup  

448
00:40:45,520 --> 00:40:50,520
muscle with the savviness to be able to get things 
done at a large organization. Fleets was run by Mo  

449
00:40:50,520 --> 00:40:57,880
Oladam, who's an entrepreneur, and Communities 
has gone through a few iterations obviously and  

450
00:40:57,880 --> 00:41:02,920
still is in the product, but John Barnett and a 
team of people who we acquired from Chroma Labs. 

451
00:41:02,920 --> 00:41:14,280
So I think that that story of acquiring hungry, 
ambitious founders and giving them responsibility  

452
00:41:14,280 --> 00:41:21,080
and latitude is a success story of Twitter's. I 
mean, I'm a beneficiary of such a bet as well.  

453
00:41:21,840 --> 00:41:26,920
My company Periscope was acquired, and I was given 
the responsibility to eventually lead the product  

454
00:41:26,920 --> 00:41:34,600
team. So I feel like that we ended up realizing, 
both through the company's history and through  

455
00:41:34,600 --> 00:41:41,400
learning, that this is actually a very effective 
way to drive cultural change and to deliver impact  

456
00:41:41,400 --> 00:41:46,200
because you need a special type of person to be 
able to both operate within the existing structure  

457
00:41:46,200 --> 00:41:52,400
and change the structure, to know when to use 
the system and to know when to fuck the system. 

458
00:41:52,400 --> 00:41:58,960
And I feel like my whole life has benefited from 
other people taking bets on me like that, to the  

459
00:41:58,960 --> 00:42:07,000
point that even I was like, "Really? You sure you 
want to?" And so I think I've enjoyed trying to  

460
00:42:07,000 --> 00:42:14,400
pass the buck and do that for other people, and 
I've never regretted it. You always, taking a bet  

461
00:42:14,400 --> 00:42:20,440
on people and especially throwing them in a deep 
end, which on paper they may be unqualified for,  

462
00:42:20,440 --> 00:42:25,680
I think is one of the best ways of driving 
change. And by the way, supporting growth,  

463
00:42:25,680 --> 00:42:30,520
you've learned so much more when you're thrown 
into the deep end than in other contexts. And so  

464
00:42:30,520 --> 00:42:34,920
I think it's fantastic, it's an expensive strategy 
if you're going to go buy a bunch of companies,  

465
00:42:34,920 --> 00:42:40,840
but it's a great strategy for the situation 
that we found ourselves in at Twitter.

466
00:42:40,840 --> 00:42:45,880
It feels like every big bet was one of these 
companies from the list that you just shared,  

467
00:42:45,880 --> 00:42:50,080
and I'm glad you shared Periscope, obviously. 
That's a great example, too. I guess maybe just  

468
00:42:50,080 --> 00:42:53,680
a follow-up question here, is there anything 
you learned about how to do this well? I know  

469
00:42:53,680 --> 00:42:57,360
you talked about maybe creating a little silo for 
the team, because so many companies acquire and  

470
00:42:57,360 --> 00:43:00,720
acquihire and they just go nowhere.
So I guess just a two-part question,  

471
00:43:00,720 --> 00:43:05,320
just like what are some tips for how to do this 
well at a company? And then, two, you also,  

472
00:43:05,320 --> 00:43:09,720
we were talking offline about this previously and 
I think it's a really interesting point, that a  

473
00:43:09,720 --> 00:43:14,720
lot of companies staff based on who's available 
versus who is right for the role, and let's wait  

474
00:43:14,720 --> 00:43:19,640
until that person is there for us to bet on 
this. Can you just talk about lessons there?

475
00:43:19,640 --> 00:43:25,680
That last one is a huge pet peeve of mine 
that I feel like we learned the hard way,  

476
00:43:25,680 --> 00:43:32,520
and particularly it's a common pattern I think 
in highly functional organizations where you  

477
00:43:32,520 --> 00:43:36,960
have different people making decisions on how to 
staff projects, and there's nothing inherently  

478
00:43:36,960 --> 00:43:42,520
wrong with that. But I think in the situations, 
in the situation we found ourselves in where we  

479
00:43:42,520 --> 00:43:48,800
had this sort of cultural evolution that we were 
going through where some people just didn't agree  

480
00:43:48,800 --> 00:43:53,440
with the things that we were prioritizing, 
they were begrudgingly going along with it,  

481
00:43:53,440 --> 00:43:57,320
but you would end up in a situation where the 
combination of that sort of cultural shift  

482
00:43:57,320 --> 00:44:03,160
and strategy and the fact that the way teams 
were being staffed was not, there's ultimately  

483
00:44:03,160 --> 00:44:07,680
no single decision maker other than the CEO and 
Jack is not going to get in the weeds and debate  

484
00:44:07,680 --> 00:44:13,280
a staffing decision on the team, resulted in a 
situation where oftentimes we'd have projects,  

485
00:44:13,280 --> 00:44:17,760
like the one I mentioned about hiding replies, 
where there wasn't even an agreement on the  

486
00:44:17,760 --> 00:44:22,840
team about whether this was a good idea and 
whether this is worth trying or how to do it. 

487
00:44:22,840 --> 00:44:29,240
And imagine, it's hard enough to build something 
from nothing. It's even harder if the team doesn't  

488
00:44:29,240 --> 00:44:35,440
believe in it. This is to the point of just being 
toxic. The startup would never succeed if all the  

489
00:44:35,440 --> 00:44:40,960
people who are working on that startup aren't to 
the point of being perhaps irrational obsessed  

490
00:44:40,960 --> 00:44:44,720
with that idea. And still willing to see truth, 
you need to be able to see whether the thing is  

491
00:44:44,720 --> 00:44:50,720
working or not, but if you don't believe it in the 
first place, I'm not betting on that succeeding. 

492
00:44:50,720 --> 00:44:56,720
And so this was common, and sometimes not as 
extreme as the examples that I mentioned, but  

493
00:44:57,480 --> 00:45:04,200
I think one of the lessons I learned, and it's 
quite intuitive actually, is you need to staff  

494
00:45:04,200 --> 00:45:08,360
projects with the team of people that are 
well equipped from a skillset standpoint,  

495
00:45:08,360 --> 00:45:13,200
but more importantly have an obsession with 
the idea they want to pursue. It's going to  

496
00:45:13,200 --> 00:45:18,280
make them work harder, it's going to make them be 
more creative. It's going to make them have the  

497
00:45:18,280 --> 00:45:23,800
sufficient level of ambition and desire to will 
this thing into existence. Because every project,  

498
00:45:23,800 --> 00:45:28,800
whether big or small, there is an element of you 
need to will this thing into existence because  

499
00:45:28,800 --> 00:45:35,520
it's hard. The only way you're going to get 
through that pain is by having that desire, and  

500
00:45:35,520 --> 00:45:40,080
I think a very easy cheat code for an organization 
to employ is to say, if you're going to work  

501
00:45:40,080 --> 00:45:44,480
on something, especially if it's speculative or 
risky, staff it with a set of people who believe  

502
00:45:44,480 --> 00:45:50,680
in it and really want to learn whether this solves 
a customer problem or not. Because if you don't  

503
00:45:50,680 --> 00:45:56,000
have that ingredient, it's going to drag everyone 
down and it's just not going to be as successful.

