00:47:06,040 --> 00:47:12,600
maybe one of the most recurring controversies of 
the podcast, is jobs-to-be-done amazing or is it  

517
00:47:12,600 --> 00:47:16,920
really bad and not something you should do? We've 
had many guests share their opinions. I feel like  

518
00:47:16,920 --> 00:47:22,120
at Twitter, jobs-to-be-done was implemented so 
strictly that it burned a lot of people out on  

519
00:47:22,120 --> 00:47:27,440
it. It's like, oh my, this is not anything anyone 
should ever do. I'm curious, just your lessons and  

520
00:47:27,440 --> 00:47:31,880
experience of just with frameworks in general, the 
jobs-to-be- done specifically, maybe even OKRs.

521
00:47:31,880 --> 00:47:37,400
I've only seen one interview on your 
show that covers this. Sriram was  

522
00:47:37,400 --> 00:47:40,360
particularly spicy when he talked about 
jobs-to-be-done, which is unsurprising  

523
00:47:40,360 --> 00:47:44,200
because. I spent a lot of time talking 
to Sriram about jobs-to-be-done. I mean,  

524
00:47:44,200 --> 00:47:47,560
I guess I'll just start by saying 
I was not a fan of how we leveraged  

525
00:47:47,560 --> 00:47:53,600
jobs-to-be-done at Twitter. I thought it 
was exhausting and not particularly helpful,  

526
00:47:53,600 --> 00:47:59,240
and so it's a particularly sore subject for me 
because I was sort of charged with defending it  

527
00:47:59,240 --> 00:48:00,715
and rolling it out. It's hard to do that when 
you don't really believe in something. But...

528
00:48:00,715 --> 00:48:05,640
It's hard to do that when you don't really believe 
in something, but to me the critique is less about  

529
00:48:05,640 --> 00:48:10,760
Jobs-to-be-Done though there are many critiques of 
it and more about every framework at its limit is  

530
00:48:10,760 --> 00:48:16,720
followed to such a religious extent it's just 
unhelpful. You need to have nuance in how you  

531
00:48:16,720 --> 00:48:23,400
leverage these frameworks. Otherwise, you lose the 
forest through the trees and you end up following  

532
00:48:23,400 --> 00:48:27,960
a process for the sake of following a process. 
And that's what happened with Jobs-to-be-Done.  

533
00:48:27,960 --> 00:48:32,480
So I think that's my real critique of it. 
It's not the... I mean listen, the premise  

534
00:48:32,480 --> 00:48:38,800
of Jobs-to-be-Done and my most charitable take on 
Jobs-to-be-Done, which is actually useful is that  

535
00:48:38,800 --> 00:48:42,880
it forces you to look at things through the lens 
of customers and understanding what their needs  

536
00:48:42,880 --> 00:48:47,440
are and understanding what their true alternatives 
are outside of the narrow lens of your product. 

537
00:48:47,440 --> 00:48:52,360
And I think that's just healthy product thinking. 
You don't need a framework called Jobs-to-be-Done.  

538
00:48:52,360 --> 00:48:55,520
You don't need to think about milkshakes in 
order to be able to do that. It's like you  

539
00:48:55,520 --> 00:49:01,320
could employ common sense or you could leverage 
something like Jobs-to-be-Done, to be able to  

540
00:49:01,320 --> 00:49:05,800
force your mind to think of things through that 
lens. So I think that's my charitable view on  

541
00:49:05,800 --> 00:49:11,680
what Jobs-to-be-Done can help you do, but as a 
framework into and of itself as a sole governing  

542
00:49:11,680 --> 00:49:17,080
principle of what to build, it's just not useful.
By the way, in the same way as, and I think  

543
00:49:17,080 --> 00:49:24,040
Twitter had this problem as well prior to our 
detour around Jobs-to-be-Done, if the only way  

544
00:49:24,040 --> 00:49:29,200
the organization is trained to think about what to 
build and what not to build is OKRs, it's equally  

545
00:49:29,200 --> 00:49:35,200
unhelpful at the limit because sure, you can have 
a good sense of what you should build to drive  

546
00:49:35,200 --> 00:49:39,680
metrics, but by the way, you might be focusing on 
the wrong metrics or that might not help you have  

547
00:49:39,680 --> 00:49:44,600
the right balance of things to build. That 
might not help you see when the things that  

548
00:49:44,600 --> 00:49:50,400
you're building are actually hostile to customers.
So just as an interesting example, the thing that  

549
00:49:50,400 --> 00:49:56,280
I remember about your interview with Shriram, 
if I'm not mistaken, I think he mentioned,  

550
00:49:57,200 --> 00:50:03,040
and I love Shriram, I'd be happy to debate him 
