555
00:50:26,200 --> 00:50:32,840
I can't search my email to see what I ordered. 
And so I think the problem with these frameworks  

556
00:50:32,840 --> 00:50:36,640
is that you lose nuance and ultimately, 
and this is where I agree with Shriram,  

557
00:50:36,640 --> 00:50:40,080
he actually mentioned this on your podcast as 
well, you need to be able to make trade-off  

558
00:50:40,080 --> 00:50:43,760
decisions that balance what's right for the 
organization and what's right for the customer. 

559
00:50:43,760 --> 00:50:48,320
And sometimes based on how you devise your 
frameworks, your metrics aren't actually  

560
00:50:48,320 --> 00:50:53,000
aligned with the customer's benefit. Like the 
Amazon example, and we had many famous examples  

561
00:50:53,000 --> 00:50:57,520
in Twitter's history, which were the same. One of 
our key metrics that we always optimized Shriram  

562
00:50:57,520 --> 00:51:04,120
growing was DAU and we had obviously the rank 
timeline did wonders for growing DAU and it  

563
00:51:04,120 --> 00:51:10,680
was a great experience for many customers, but we 
often had features that would not lead to a good  

564
00:51:10,680 --> 00:51:17,200
customer experience and the team would just be 
blind towards leaving hostile customer experiences  

565
00:51:17,200 --> 00:51:21,200
in place because it was good for metrics and 
aggregate. And the famous example of this is  

566
00:51:21,200 --> 00:51:26,640
we had this toggle, which we called Swish very 
