these features basically and make them work. And 
they did a lot of other savvy things too from a  

723
01:05:13,560 --> 01:05:21,320
partnership standpoint. We had a lot of prominent 
streamers that ranged from influencer or just  

724
01:05:21,320 --> 01:05:25,640
creative people that became known on Periscopes, 
all the way up to celebrities like Kevin Hart and  

725
01:05:26,520 --> 01:05:30,600
others who were prolific Periscopers 
that Facebook just went and bought out. 

726
01:05:30,600 --> 01:05:35,160
They were just like, "Cool, we're going to pay you 
a bunch of money to stream exclusively with us."  

727
01:05:35,160 --> 01:05:41,400
So they hit us from all sides. They had the entire 
company put their effort towards building live in  

728
01:05:41,400 --> 01:05:47,080
a way that was cohesive in the core product first 
with Facebook and then Instagram and then also  

729
01:05:47,080 --> 01:05:56,520
attacked it from the creator as well. And we 
were too slow and it was very painful to think  

730
01:05:56,520 --> 01:06:05,680
about because it was like many other insights that 
Twitter had early. Twitter had the right insight,  

731
01:06:05,680 --> 01:06:10,040
but botched the follow through. I'm not pointing 
fingers, I blame myself for that just as much,  

732
01:06:10,800 --> 01:06:16,960
but there's a pattern where Twitter is really 
great at spotting meaningful consumer behavior  

733
01:06:16,960 --> 01:06:21,840
changes. They spotted Vine and acquired 
Vine, botched it, spotted Periscope,  

734
01:06:21,840 --> 01:06:27,640
botched it, spotted Instagram by the way, 
before Facebook tried to buy Instagram,  

735
01:06:27,640 --> 01:06:30,840
Twitter was trying to buy Instagram, and there 
are other reasons why that didn't fall through,  

736
01:06:30,840 --> 01:06:35,440
but it's interesting to me, it's one of the 
interesting aspects of Twitter's history. 

737
01:06:35,440 --> 01:06:40,720
They were phenomenal at spotting meaningful 
changes in consumer social behavior,  

738
01:06:40,720 --> 01:06:45,080
and actually putting their money where their 
mouth is in terms of trying to follow through  

739
01:06:45,080 --> 01:06:51,480
on bringing those bets in-house, but then botching 
the execution. And so that was one of the things  

740
01:06:51,480 --> 01:06:58,400
that was really motivating for me when I was in 
my role leading product of Twitter was I didn't  

741
01:06:58,400 --> 01:07:08,280
want to make that mistake and we didn't end as 
up buying anything like Vine or Periscope and  

742
01:07:08,280 --> 01:07:15,760
keeping the product. We obviously bought lots 
of small acquirers, but we did obviously have  

743
01:07:15,760 --> 01:07:21,400
a bit of a story with Clubhouse that ended 
up with us building Spaces and competing  

744
01:07:21,400 --> 01:07:25,160
with them. But anyway, that was a long, rambly 
story. Hopefully that answered your question.

745
01:07:25,160 --> 01:07:28,520
Yeah, there's so many. Again, it's all these 
fractals of thought threads I want to follow  

746
01:07:28,520 --> 01:07:32,840
and ask you about. Real quick on the Vine and 
Periscope point, I was going to ask this. Twitter,  

747
01:07:32,840 --> 01:07:36,920
as you said, had the opportunity to win in 
video in so many ways. Vine was amazing,  

748
01:07:36,920 --> 01:07:40,720
killing everyone, loved it, and then it's 
fades away. I guess, you already shared  

749
01:07:40,720 --> 01:07:45,880
a lot of challenges Twitter had with executing, 
shipping, Secret Cows, things like that. Is there  

750
01:07:45,880 --> 01:07:49,480
anything specific with video? Was it just like, 
oh, this is not actually a huge priority and we're  

751
01:07:49,480 --> 01:07:53,720
just going to ride it for now and that's why it 
didn't work out? Or is there anything more that?

752
01:07:53,720 --> 01:08:01,440
No, it's even more like pathetic than that 'cause 
I think Twitter did believe in video, but it made  

753
01:08:01,440 --> 01:08:07,880
this classical mistake that we also unfortunately 
recreated with Periscope, which was they had the  

754
01:08:07,880 --> 01:08:14,040
insight around short-run video, they bought Vine. 
They then competed with Vine internally. So Vine  

755
01:08:14,040 --> 01:08:19,880
was a separate organization within Twitter, 
separate office obviously in New York and then  

756
01:08:19,880 --> 01:08:25,440
Twitter rather than integrated holistically 
into the product and pour gasoline on it,  

757
01:08:27,080 --> 01:08:32,480
they built a native Twitter video feature that 
was a different stack, different team. It became  

758
01:08:32,480 --> 01:08:36,080
what you think of as Twitter video now. It's 
like the most simple active uploading video  

759
01:08:36,080 --> 01:08:43,120
and all the professional video tools called Media 
Studio that let publishers like ESPN put content.  

760
01:08:43,120 --> 01:08:46,680
All of that was basically built as a separate 
team, separate organization, separate product  

761
01:08:46,680 --> 01:08:52,160
that was competing with Vine. You had two visions 
for short form video that were manifesting, and  

762
01:08:52,160 --> 01:09:01,800
that's the quickest way for things to get messy.
And of course the separate startup team is going  

763
01:09:01,800 --> 01:09:07,920
to get, you're not going to be able to make 
good on the vision of buying the company  

764
01:09:07,920 --> 01:09:13,360
and integrating it in all the right ways if 
you compete with it internally. And we had a  

765
01:09:13,360 --> 01:09:20,680
similar thing happen with Periscope. We were very 
focused on Periscope with separate organizations,  

766
01:09:20,680 --> 01:09:25,360
separate structures, separate app. Periscope at 
the time primarily was focused on UGC live video.  

767
01:09:26,320 --> 01:09:32,480
So user-generated content being streamed from a 
phone. Twitter then decided to get in the premium  

768
01:09:32,480 --> 01:09:39,320
live video business very famously with acquiring 
rights to Thursday night football, the NFL. Guess  

769
01:09:39,320 --> 01:09:47,160
what happened? We competed internally rather than 
have a cohesive technical and product vision for  

770
01:09:47,160 --> 01:09:53,920
how to embrace live video across the spectrum 
of UGC and premium live video, Twitter put a  

771
01:09:53,920 --> 01:10:02,160
separate team in charge of premium with a separate 
product, separate technology stack. And so you had  

772
01:10:02,160 --> 01:10:06,760
two ways to manifest live video on the product. 
It was like UGC live video, which was awkwardly  

773
01:10:06,760 --> 01:10:10,720
not even really implemented well with Twitter 
at the time. And then premium live video, which  

774
01:10:10,720 --> 01:10:14,880
had totally different UX, total different team, 
totally different architecture. And by the way,  

775
01:10:14,880 --> 01:10:19,880
the company put a tremendous amount of energy 
and investment in talking about Twitter being  

776
01:10:19,880 --> 01:10:25,720
a place to watch the NFL. And meanwhile you had 
this burgeoning UGC ecosystem, so this was like  

777
01:10:25,720 --> 01:10:30,520
we're making the same mistake all over again. 
Now, luckily in the Periscope case with a lot  

778
01:10:30,520 --> 01:10:36,400
of persistence and impatience and table pounding, 
we eventually fixed that mistake, but we wasted  

779
01:10:36,400 --> 01:10:43,000
a tremendous amount of time. It was just a lot of 
headbutting in politics and eventually it took us  

780
01:10:43,000 --> 01:10:48,680
a lot of time to technically reintegrate things 
together and now it's clean and awesome, right? 

781
01:10:48,680 --> 01:10:53,720
ESPN can go live with behind the scenes content 
at Wimbledon and it's the same technology stack  

782
01:10:53,720 --> 01:10:59,160
and the same user experience, the powers, Lenny 
going live from his iPhone. But I think that was  

783
01:10:59,160 --> 01:11:05,320
one of the reasons why it was an example of failed 
execution that ended up wasting time, resources  

784
01:11:05,320 --> 01:11:11,880
and just leading to a subpar product experience 
that other companies I think have avoided making  

785
01:11:11,880 --> 01:11:17,720
such mistakes. Facebook being a prime example, 
as frustrated, I am with them as a competitor  

786
01:11:17,720 --> 01:11:25,600
for having really taken over the use case for 
live video. Got to hand it to them, brilliant  

787
01:11:25,600 --> 01:11:33,800
execution, have a lot of respect for them. So we 
made sure to not make that mistake moving forward.

788
01:11:33,800 --> 01:11:38,040
I imagine there was reason for that. Partly I 
imagine this calcification of just like, we can't  

789
01:11:38,040 --> 01:11:41,760
get you done, we just need to start a new team 
and do this thing. I imagine it always comes from  

790
01:11:41,760 --> 01:11:47,440
like, oh, this makes sense. And then you realize, 
okay, this was a terrible idea down the road.

791
01:11:47,440 --> 01:11:52,520
Yeah, it's that and also leadership. When you 
don't have unified leadership around these things,  

792
01:11:52,520 --> 01:11:57,040
you end up making decisions that are in 
conflict with one another. They're just  

793
01:11:57,040 --> 01:12:01,920
need a highly opinionated person at the top 
that avoids that kind of messiness from a.

794
01:12:01,920 --> 01:12:05,840
That kind of messiness from a 
product and engineering standpoint.

795
01:12:05,840 --> 01:12:13,040
You mentioned Clubhouse, so I think what's 
interesting is one, many people copy Periscope as  

796
01:12:13,040 --> 01:12:17,680
a product. I don't know if you'll describe it as 
copying, but it feels like spaces very inspired by  

797
01:12:17,680 --> 01:12:24,280
Clubhouse. Do you have just a current philosophy 
on when it makes sense to be super inspired by  

798
01:12:24,280 --> 01:12:30,360
another product and build it into your existing 
product versus like, no, you should not do this?

799
01:12:30,360 --> 01:12:37,480
I think it's always about doing the right 
thing for the customer. Everyone has always  

800
01:12:37,480 --> 01:12:41,360
been shameless to be shamelessly inspired by 
other people's ideas. I don't think there's  

801
01:12:41,360 --> 01:12:46,200
anything wrong with that. I think copying 
ideas can be done in poor taste and can be  

802
01:12:46,200 --> 01:12:53,440
done with taste. I think some of the people 
who copied Periscope did so in poor taste,  

803
01:12:53,440 --> 01:13:00,720
can't blame them. I wouldn't have done it the 
same way, but it worked. So you can't say it's the  

804
01:13:00,720 --> 01:13:07,760
wrong thing. I think that it's possible to take 
ideas in good taste and take ideas in poor taste. 

805
01:13:07,760 --> 01:13:13,600
And I think with Clubhouse, we actually had 
been working on audio. Audio was one of those  

806
01:13:13,600 --> 01:13:17,920
bets I mentioned that we structured 
very separately with a team of people,  

807
01:13:17,920 --> 01:13:23,400
many of which were the former Periscope team, 
that when we wound down Periscope, I felt very  

808
01:13:23,400 --> 01:13:29,640
strongly that there was still something to the 
idea of synchronous conversations. Because one  

809
01:13:29,640 --> 01:13:34,720
of the famous things that I think we botched 
with Periscope is that we always... Our dream  

810
01:13:34,720 --> 01:13:39,080
and our vision for Periscope and how we talked 
about it was was a mechanism for teleportation.  

811
01:13:39,080 --> 01:13:42,520
You could see through someone else's eyes and be 
teleported somewhere else. It was like that was  

812
01:13:42,520 --> 01:13:46,880
the story we told ourselves. That was the thing 
that inspired Periscope. And to a certain extent,  

813
01:13:46,880 --> 01:13:51,560
a lot of people did use the product for that way. 
You could go see what it was like someplace in the  

814
01:13:51,560 --> 01:13:56,160
world where it was something amazing happening 
or civil unrest happening or some important  

815
01:13:56,160 --> 01:14:00,920
moment happening with breaking news or otherwise.
But it turns out the vast majority of our users  

816
01:14:00,920 --> 01:14:06,840
were not using Periscope that way. It wasn't 
a rear-facing camera experience where you were  

817
01:14:06,840 --> 01:14:10,800
showing someone the world, the vast majority 
of people were using it to just talk to other  

818
01:14:10,800 --> 01:14:15,840
people. They were bored or they were lonely and 
they wanted to just have a conversation with other  

819
01:14:15,840 --> 01:14:19,920
people. And it turns out video and audio is a very 
interesting way of doing that that allows for more  

820
01:14:19,920 --> 01:14:25,040
nuance, more long-form conversation, more in-depth 
conversation, especially in contracts to Twitter,  

821
01:14:26,040 --> 01:14:33,240
which has mechanics to really incentivize quick, 
snappy broadcasts that don't lead to much depth.  

822
01:14:33,240 --> 01:14:38,200
And so when we shut down Periscope, we were 
like, man, we really need to enable a new  

823
01:14:38,200 --> 01:14:43,000
form of conversation on Twitter that has some 
of those properties. And so we had a team that  

824
01:14:43,000 --> 01:14:49,520
was working on a project that we sort of 
code named Hydra. Hydra because there were  

825
01:14:49,520 --> 01:14:54,480
multiple heads on this monster and those 
heads are participants in a conversation. 

826
01:14:54,480 --> 01:14:58,720
And so well before Clubhouse was on the 
map, we had many different iterations  

827
01:14:58,720 --> 01:15:03,640
of both video and audio only experiences that 
just didn't feel right, weren't working right,  

828
01:15:03,640 --> 01:15:11,200
but we felt like we were onto something. And when 
Clubhouse came on the map, it really re-centered,  

829
01:15:11,200 --> 01:15:16,320
it put into focus a user experience that felt a 
lot more right and now give them complete credit  

830
01:15:16,320 --> 01:15:21,840
for that. Paul and Rohan and that team did an 
exceptional job crafting an experience that  

831
01:15:21,840 --> 01:15:27,360
really enabled that mechanic and that premise 
of enabling these longer form conversations to  

832
01:15:27,360 --> 01:15:32,720
shine. And so we did shamelessly seek inspiration 
from what they had done and what had worked and we  

833
01:15:32,720 --> 01:15:39,240
put our own spin on it. The execution of Spaces 
within Twitter I think has some similarities,  

834
01:15:39,240 --> 01:15:42,720
but also really took advantage of the mechanics 
that you had available to you in Twitter. It's a  

835
01:15:42,720 --> 01:15:49,280
different product. And so we took the ideas that 
we felt were shortcuts to making the experience  

836
01:15:49,280 --> 01:15:55,480
work and then we put our own spin on it. And 
so I have no problems with what we did there. 

837
01:15:55,480 --> 01:16:05,080
And having had experienced the pain of not 
moving quickly enough with Vine from the  

838
01:16:05,080 --> 01:16:12,440
outside and Periscope having lived that 
experience, we were not willing to not be  

839
01:16:12,440 --> 01:16:21,120
the winner with this use case. It is one of the 
projects I'm most proud of that we worked on at  

840
01:16:21,120 --> 01:16:28,120
Twitter because we were very radical in our 
execution. Hydra went from this tiny project  

841
01:16:28,120 --> 01:16:34,000
that six people were working on that no one knew 
or care about to, we made Spaces as the number one  

842
01:16:34,000 --> 01:16:41,760
priority of the company literally above any other 
project period. And we put a bunch of people on  

843
01:16:41,760 --> 01:16:49,840
accelerating that product and making it come 
to life within Twitter. And a lot of that was  

844
01:16:49,840 --> 01:16:56,080
having felt the pain and burn of fucking this 
up with Vine and Periscope. And so I'm really  

845
01:16:56,080 --> 01:16:59,880
proud of our execution. And it was also really 
energizing. I hope for the company to see that,  

846
01:16:59,880 --> 01:17:08,000
wow, we pulled that off. So yeah, it was good. It 
was nice to have that full circle experience and  

847
01:17:08,000 --> 01:17:15,600
also nice that, personally, I love that aspects 
of Periscope continue living on within Twitter.

848
01:17:15,600 --> 01:17:19,120
I did not know that. That is extremely 
interesting. Speaking full circle,  

849
01:17:19,120 --> 01:17:24,320
when I joined Clubhouse the first time, Paul was 
there introducing me to Clubhouse and exactly the  

850
01:17:24,320 --> 01:17:30,520
way you described Periscope, so I feel like he 
drew some inspiration from you one step back.

851
01:17:30,520 --> 01:17:36,480
Paul's amazing. I feel like we're kindred spirits 
and I could see... It was one of the things I love  

852
01:17:36,480 --> 01:17:42,680
about that team is just you could just feel how 
palpable their excitement was and their passion  

853
01:17:42,680 --> 01:17:49,720
was for what they were building. Another universe 
we could have worked together more closely,  

854
01:17:50,280 --> 01:17:58,120
but I think what they built was incredible and 
we took inspiration from it for sure. Yeah.

855
01:17:58,120 --> 01:18:03,400
So you've built some of the most successful, 
most beloved, most used consumer products.  

856
01:18:03,400 --> 01:18:08,040
You continue to help other founders with their 
product. I'm curious just if you have any advice  

857
01:18:08,040 --> 01:18:13,760
for how to get better at building consumer 
products in terms of maybe craft a product,  

858
01:18:13,760 --> 01:18:19,680
product sense. What have you learned about what 
it takes to build a successful consumer product?

859
01:18:19,680 --> 01:18:24,320
The best cheat codes for getting better at 
building products is just being a voracious user  

860
01:18:24,320 --> 01:18:32,680
of products. And just trying new things, feeling 
out what works well, what doesn't, what you like,  

861
01:18:32,680 --> 01:18:39,440
what you don't like. There's just no replacement 
for that. It's such an effective way of honing  

862
01:18:39,440 --> 01:18:46,640
your own taste and seeing what's superficial 
but not useful, what's ugly but useful,  

863
01:18:46,640 --> 01:18:53,960
what's beautiful and useful. And you hone that by 
having practice and building muscle memory. And  

864
01:18:54,920 --> 01:19:01,560
so I think there's not a lot of science to it, 
I think. I mean obviously science can help you  

865
01:19:01,560 --> 01:19:04,960
become more effective at lots of things. 
But I feel like I've just always been very  

866
01:19:04,960 --> 01:19:12,800
curious about trying new things. I'm a very hungry 
consumer of new things that people are building  

867
01:19:12,800 --> 01:19:17,800
and I'm not quick to judge. I'll try it even if 
it seems dumb because sometimes things that seem  

868
01:19:17,800 --> 01:19:22,560
dumb at the beginning become very meaningful.
And so it's always been a very helpful cheat  

869
01:19:22,560 --> 01:19:29,600
code for me. And it's also just personally 
interesting. Every tool, even the silly ones,  

870
01:19:29,600 --> 01:19:33,160
people put their heart and soul into it and it's 
like an expression of themselves and it's always  

871
01:19:33,160 --> 01:19:38,440
interesting to see that, to see people's creations 
and to learn from them and see what you like,  

872
01:19:38,440 --> 01:19:44,080
what you don't like and how you might create 
something of your own that borrows from that.  

873
01:19:44,080 --> 01:19:51,400
So if I could give people any advice through 
the lens of what's worked for me, it's that.

874
01:19:51,400 --> 01:19:55,080
Speaking of trying new things, 
what are you up to these days?

875
01:19:55,080 --> 01:20:02,240
I'm building something in the consumer space. I 
started the company with a couple of co-founders  

876
01:20:02,240 --> 01:20:07,800
late last year. We're not quite ready to 
talk about it yet, but hopefully you'll be  

877
01:20:07,800 --> 01:20:13,080
hearing from us pretty soon. But it's really 
nice to be back building something again,  

878
01:20:13,080 --> 01:20:18,440
particularly building something with a small 
team again after seeing the opposite extreme  

879
01:20:18,440 --> 01:20:24,920
with a really large company. We've just talked 
about lots of large company things. But yeah,  

880
01:20:24,920 --> 01:20:26,760
hopefully you'll be hearing about it soon.

881
01:20:26,760 --> 01:20:32,080
Oh man, I think this is breaking news. 
So mysterious and exciting. Kayvon,  

882
01:20:32,080 --> 01:20:35,120
is there anything else you wanted to 
share or leave listeners with before  

883
01:20:35,120 --> 01:20:38,960
we get to our very exciting lightning round?

884
01:20:38,960 --> 01:20:42,200
No, no, I think we've covered quite a bit.

885
01:20:42,200 --> 01:20:47,560
We have. We have indeed. With that, we've reached 
our very exciting lightning round. Are you ready?

886
01:20:47,560 --> 01:20:50,160
I'm going to take a sip of 
water and then I'll be ready.

887
01:20:50,160 --> 01:20:51,320
Okay, here we go. First question,  

888
01:20:51,320 --> 01:20:54,640
what are two or three books that you've 
recommended most to other people?

889
01:20:54,640 --> 01:21:02,000
I love reading sci-fi. I just feel like 
sci-fi and mystery books are so healthy  

890
01:21:02,000 --> 01:21:08,520
for jogging the imagination. And so some of 
my favorite books are by Neal Stephenson,  

891
01:21:08,520 --> 01:21:16,880
I love Cryptonomicon. I love Reamde. I love a 
book called Name of the Wind by Patrick Rothfuss,  

892
01:21:16,880 --> 01:21:27,520
which is more like a fantasy book, but I just 
love escaping reality and thinking about sci-fi,  

893
01:21:27,520 --> 01:21:34,440
thinking about fantasy is just, it's helpful 
for the soul and helpful for the imagination.  

894
01:21:34,440 --> 01:21:39,040
So those are some of my favorite reads 
because it helps me. I feel like in some  

895
01:21:39,040 --> 01:21:45,160
weird circular or wandering way, it helps me be 
more creative and imaginative. And by the way,  

896
01:21:45,160 --> 01:21:49,240
that's true outside of reading as well. 
Some of the content that has shaped me,  

897
01:21:49,240 --> 01:21:56,040
I feel like and help motivate my curiosity and a 
lot of things I built is sci-fi TV, right? Star  

898
01:21:56,040 --> 01:22:04,440
Trek is incredible. We used to use as a metaphor 
for what Periscope was, we would think about Star  

899
01:22:04,440 --> 01:22:10,320
Trek. It'd be really cool to be able to teleport 
or get beamed somewhere else in the world and  

900
01:22:10,320 --> 01:22:14,800
we're not smart enough to go build that device, 
but what's the closest approximation to that that  

901
01:22:14,800 --> 01:22:24,400
we can realize through software? Live streaming. 
So I think that kind of literature or content  

902
01:22:25,000 --> 01:22:30,680
has always been inspirational for me and I think 
getting that through books is really healthy.

903
01:22:30,680 --> 01:22:34,440
On that note, is there a favorite 
recent movie or TV show that's  

904
01:22:34,440 --> 01:22:37,520
inspired you in addition to 
Star Trek back in the day?

905
01:22:37,520 --> 01:22:41,080
I mean the most recent movie I saw in 
theaters was Dune Two, and it was incredible.

906
01:22:41,080 --> 01:22:41,800
I just saw that.

907
01:22:41,800 --> 01:22:48,320
It's insane. I also thought Oppenheimer was... I'm 
a huge Nolan fan. Oppenheimer was captivating. To  

